eId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Browne IM, Andr&#xe9; F, Chandarlapaty S, Carey LA, Turner NC. Optimal targeting of PI3K-AKT and mTOR in advanced oestrogen receptor-positive breast cancer. Lancet Oncol. 2024;25:e139&#x2013;51. doi: 10.1016/s1470-2045(23)00676-9.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1016/s1470-2045(23)00676-9</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">38547898</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Pang KH, Rugo HS, Wallace T, Kelly G, Paley D, Miller K, et al. Clinical investigators&#x2019; (CIs) practice patterns for patients with hormone receptor-positive metastatic breast cancer (HR+ mBC) harboring PI3K/AKT/PTEN pathway abnormalities (PAPm) J Clin Oncol. 2025;43:e43. doi: 10.1200/jco.2025.43.16_suppl.e13091.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1200/jco.2025.43.16_suppl.e13091</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>SERENA-2 Trial: Camizestrant Improves Progression-Free Survival in Advanced Breast Cancer [Internet]  The ASCO Post; 2023 [cited 2026 Jan 25]. Available from: https://ascopost.com/issues/january-25-2023/camizestrant-improves-progression-free-survival-in-advanced-breast-cancer/ </Citation></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">42169538</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>18</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>18</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1744-7666</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>27</Volume><Issue>9</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jun</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Expert opinion on pharmacotherapy</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Expert Opin Pharmacother</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Oral selective estrogen receptor degraders (SERDs) for the treatment of hormone receptor-positive, HER2-negative breast cancer title.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>773</StartPage><EndPage>786</EndPage><MedlinePgn>773-786</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1080/14656566.2026.2678481</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="INTRODUCTION" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Endocrine therapy (ET) remains the backbone of treatment for hormone receptor-positive (HR+), HER2-negative breast cancer. However, resistance, frequently driven by acquired <i>ESR1</i> mutations detected in up to 40% of patients progressing on first-line ET, represents a major clinical challenge. Oral selective estrogen receptor degraders (SERDs) have been developed to overcome the limitations of first-generation agents and achieve more potent ER targeting.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="AREAS COVERED" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">This review summarizes the mechanism of action of oral SERDs compared with prior endocrine therapies and evaluates clinical evidence supporting their use across treatment settings in HR+/HER2- breast cancer. Literature was identified through systematic searches of PubMed, ClinicalTrials.gov, and major oncology congresses (ASCO, ESMO, SABCS) through early 2026.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="EXPERT OPINION" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Oral SERDs are reshaping the management of <i>ESR1</i>-mutant disease, with agents such as elacestrant and imlunestrant emerging as standard second-line options. In early-stage disease, trials such as lidERA suggest potential outcome improvements. However, primary resistance to SERD monotherapy remains substantial, highlighting the need for combination strategies. Future directions include ctDNA-guided approaches and expansion into earlier treatment settings.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Etessami</LastName><ForeName>Julian David</ForeName><Initials>JD</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of New Drugs and Early Drug Development for 